The appointment of a. dictator at this crisis, or when any special work was to be done, shows an elasticity in the official arrangements at Rome. It was impossible that with annual magistrates, such as consuls or military tribunes, the best men should always be chosen. Theoreti- cally, the various officials and magistrates could produce a deadloek in public business, if theywere in conflict3 but on the whole, the system was not without singular merits.
